---
The Compact of the Seven Chains was an agreement between seven warring eastern clans that ended
a clan-war cycle during the Iron Reformation period by establishing mutual rules of engagement—
specifically including the creation of a new officer class bound by Compact terms regardless
of which clan employed them. This was a foundational political innovation: an officer tradition
whose primary institutional loyalty was to shared doctrine rather than to any individual employer.
Each clan's interest in having enemies who adhered to predictable engagement rules, which made
post-battle political negotiations more reliable, outweighed their interest in unrestricted
armies. The first Knights trained under the Compact's framework: body mechanics, controlled
aggression, and formation superiority as foundational doctrine. The Compact's motto—break the
line, hold the ground, leave no fallen comrade behind—encoded three distinct doctrinal
commitments in productive tension with each other. The Compact did not produce merely soldiers;
it produced practitioners whose formation discipline reliably outperformed greater numbers of
individually trained fighters who could not maintain coherent system operation under sustained
pressure. Its modern legacy is the Knight tradition and the ongoing question of whether doctrine
loyalty supersedes employer loyalty when the two conflict.

